snippet.textDisplay:
From the scientific experts:
1. Donna Moralejo, a professor in Memorial University's faculty of nursing who specializes in infection control, says there is little scientific evidence homemade masks can prevent covid-19 or stop spread of covid-19, but they can cause increased exposure.
2. The World Health Organization (WHO) on the other hand argues that surgical face masks should only be worn by carers and not by the general public.
3. MIT study showed, "One of the main points of argument is that viruses are tiny and would be able to penetrate most surgical face masks.

“What confuses people about surgical mask use is whether it provides absolute protection; does it stop all virus? The answer to that, for most masks, is no."
4. "While the tide has turned toward a more pro-medical mask approach in the U.S., some experts have reservations about the policy. Cloth masks are poorly studied, and there isn’t much real-world evidence to recommend medical masks to the general public. Such guidelines could also exacerbate shortages of medical masks or backfire if people don’t wear their coverings properly or if they are lulled into a false sense of security." University of Chicago Study.
5. Dated April 6 , 2020: "The scientific and technical advisory committee said that the virus can only be transmitted via droplets and surfaces on which it can survive for up to three hours. Social distancing and washing hands frequently are the best ways to reduce the chances of that happening, rather than wearing a medical mask, the WHO said."
6. "Medical face masks are generally used to prevent the spread of airborne viruses, which COVID-19 is not. Coronavirus spreads from person to person via respiratory droplets that are produced when someone who is infected coughs or sneezes, according to the CDC.
Surgical masks can be useful in theory, says Dr. Sovndal. "If someone were to sneeze, and there was a droplet, it could protect you toor face from that droplet," he explains. But, coronavirus may enter through other areas like your eyes — especially if you touch your face."(April 8, 2020).
7. "If there is a benefit to having healthy people mask up, the effect is likely to be too small. No one should assume they are protected by a face mask, and it’s critical that people continue to stay six feet away from others and keep washing their hands. As the CDC says, cloth coverings are "not a substitute" for social distancing."

snippet.textDisplay: Be mindful that many states and municipalities have laws against covering your face in public, (and just because your mayor requests something does not change the law or suspend the law) so if you wear one of these outside you may be violating the law. We like to think that our law enforcement officials are reasonable, but its not always the case. The last thing you want right now is to be interacting with law enforcement, so just be aware of the laws in your area and be prepared to deal with an officer who may want to make an example out of you, have a plan for how to handle that situation.   I wonder if we will see these laws repealed in the future so people can just wear their ski masks around in public and not have to go through the trouble of making one of these?
